


On Azure (Azure AI Foundry)

Microsoft Phi-4-mini

Phi-4-mini is a 3.8 billion parameter model trained on 5 trillion tokens. It supports a 128K context window and handles text-based tasks like reasoning, math, and instruction following well for its size. It is natively available in Azure AI Foundry and on Hugging Face. Being a Microsoft model, it gets first-class treatment on Azure, including fine-tuning support and managed endpoints.

Microsoft Phi-4-multimodal

This one handles speech, vision, and text together. It outperforms WhisperV3 on automatic speech recognition benchmarks and sits at the top of the Hugging Face OpenASR leaderboard. Available in Azure AI Foundry, it is a solid pick if you need one model that can deal with more than just text.

Microsoft Phi-3 and Phi-3.5 Mini

The previous generation of the Phi family. Phi-3.5 Mini at 3.8B parameters is still widely deployed because of its strong reasoning and long-context performance. Available in Azure AI Studio with MIT licensing, ONNX support, and fine-tuning options. Phi-3-mini is also light enough to run on-device if needed.

Meta Llama 3.1 8B and Llama 3.2 (1B, 3B)

All of these are in the Azure AI Foundry model catalog. The 8B is a good general-purpose option for chat, summarization, and code tasks without paying OpenAI pricing. The 1B and 3B variants from Llama 3.2 are meant for edge and on-device use, but they are available in Foundry as well for cloud testing and fine-tuning.

Mistral Small 3 and Mistral NeMo

Mistral Small 3 is a 24B parameter model that runs about three times faster than comparable models and benchmarks close to Llama 3.3 70B. Mistral NeMo is a 12B model built together with NVIDIA, good for multilingual tasks. Both are available in the Azure AI Foundry catalog. Azure has had a strong partnership with Mistral, so the models come with managed API access and content safety filters built in.

Qwen series (smaller variants)

The Qwen models from Alibaba are available in the Foundry catalog as well. The smaller variants like 1.5B and 7B are useful if you need strong multilingual coverage, especially for Chinese language tasks. They support 4-bit quantization for cheaper inference.


On Google Cloud (Vertex AI Model Garden)

Gemma 3 family

Gemma 3 is Google's own open-weight SLM family and the most native option for Vertex AI. The lineup includes a 1B, 4B, 12B, and 27B variant. Gemma 3 1B can be deployed directly to a GPU-backed Vertex AI endpoint and is one of the smallest usable models available. The 4B version is multimodal, supporting both text and images with a 128K context window. Gemma 3n is the mobile-first variant using selective parameter activation, so memory usage stays low even though the raw parameter count is higher. All Gemma models are open-weight and fine-tunable through Vertex AI.

Meta Llama 3.1 8B and Llama 3.2 (1B, 3B)

Available in Vertex AI Model Garden with both managed API and self-hosted deployment options. The 1B and 3B variants are listed specifically for on-device and edge inference. You can deploy them to a Vertex AI endpoint or to Google Kubernetes Engine for more control over configuration.

Mistral Small 3.1 (25.03)

This is the compact Mistral option available on Vertex AI as a managed serverless API. It has multimodal capabilities, handles up to 128K context, and is designed for low-latency workloads. Good for programming, reasoning, and document understanding. No infrastructure to manage; you call it through the Vertex AI API endpoint and pay as you go.

Codestral 2 by Mistral

Available in Vertex AI Model Garden as a managed API. Built specifically for code generation and fill-in-the-middle completion. Useful for developer tools and coding assistants where you want a small, fast, specialized model rather than a general one.

Qwen3 and Qwen 2.5

Qwen3 was added to Vertex AI Model Garden in 2025. Like on Azure, the smaller Qwen variants are useful for multilingual applications and cost-conscious deployments. You can self-host or use them through the model catalog depending on your setup.


Quick take

For Azure, the Phi family is the easiest starting point because of how tightly it integrates with Azure AI Foundry, fine-tuning pipelines, and Microsoft's safety tooling. Mistral and Llama are strong alternatives when you want something more community-tested or provider-neutral.

For Google Cloud, Gemma 3 is the most seamless option since it is Google's own model family and is deeply integrated with Vertex AI and GKE. Mistral Small 3.1 is worth a look for low-latency production use via the managed API, and Qwen3 is a good call if multilingual support is a priority.
